<title>Swallows</title>
<summary><i>Stones must not be thrown at the !kuerri-|nan (a little bird which is supposed to belong to the Rain). The evil effects of so doing exemplified in the case of the narrator’s cousin. In the Katkop dialect, by Díä!kwãin (L V.-21. 5698-5707).</i> Children should respect swallows and not throw stones at them, for fear of being killed or made ill by sorcerers. Kki-a ||ken fainted and got ill after throwing stones at a swallow with some other little boys when he was a child.</summary><comments>1) p.5698v: swallows eat little insects that live in water, 2) pp.5702v &amp; 5703v: see<i> Kki-a-||ken who threw stones at swallows,</i> 3) This story is found in Book V-21</comments><date>15 December 1875 (started)</date><storypages>5698-5707</storypages><category>Custom and daily life</category><category>History (personal)</category><category>Plants and animals</category><category>The Rain and Rain&apos;s water</category><author>Dia!kwain (David Hoesar) (V)</author><keyword><kw>swallow</kw><subkw>called !kuerri-|nan</subkw></keyword>
